english:
  title: Epitaph for Chamberlain Han, Marquis of Cheongseong, with Preface
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the fourteenth year of the present reign, the Chamberlain first received appointment as Vice Director of the Secretariat. That winter, when an envoy was to be sent to the Yuan capital to offer New Year's greetings, the ministers entered court and spoke thus: "Now the Yuan Chancellor stands armed in the palace courtyard, commanding all under heaven. The court reception and assemblies are unlike those of former days. We find it difficult to select a suitable envoy, and humbly beseech you." That very day an edict came forth: "None but Han shall suffice." The Chamberlain was summoned and the sovereign addressed him directly: "When you went to offer felicitations on my birthday in the year of Ding-You, your journey was smooth and your return brought no word of trouble. For this I have held you in esteem and have not forgotten you even now. Go again with reverence." The Chamberlain bowed twice in gratitude and replied: "This unworthy servant holds only a position in the Secretariat, possessing no special talent to repay even a ten-thousandth of Your Majesty's grace. How could I dare refuse this mission?" He departed and returned having indeed pleased the sovereign. Not long after, he was enfeoffed as a marquis and retired to his estate, though we still hoped his recall would not be long in coming. Alas, how swiftly the end came.

    The Chamberlain was of the Han clan, whose ancestral home was Cheongju through many generations. In the distant past there was an ancestor named Lan, who rendered service at the founding of the kingdom and received the title of Merit Subject of the Three Hans. Among his descendants, the most renowned was one named Kang, who under the reign of King Won administered the examinations at the National Academy and served Kings Chungnyeol as examiner twice, retiring as Councilor with the posthumous name Munhae. Munhae begat the Remonstrator Sagi, who begat the Duke of Sangdang Ak, posthumously named Sasuk. When King Chungmok was slandered at the Yuan court, Sasuk devised a clever stratagem to secure his safe return. He then served King Chunghye twice as Chancellor and received sacrifice in the Great Temple. Sasuk married the daughter of Won Kyeong, Joint Director of the Secretariat, and fathered five sons. The eldest, Dae-sun, died in office as Inspector of the Censorate. Jungrye and Bangshin both became Secretariat Literati. Our Chamberlain was the second among them. The brothers were devoted to one another, and people of the time admired them greatly. Among them was one named Gakseong who studied Buddhist teachings and composed in the Jogye tradition.

    The Chamberlain's name was Gongui and his courtesy name Uiji. He lived fifty-nine years. He first received office through hereditary privilege as Recorder of the Lower Ministry, and was early recognized by King Chunghye, rapidly advancing through the ranks to become Major General and Right Censor of the Three Departments. His composure and steadfastness earned him the enmity of those who wielded power, and he was sent out as Governor of Jeonju, where his administration brought benefit to the people. Under King Chungmok he served as judge of three ministries. When called to serve as Drafter under King Chungjeong, on the day the king retired from power, he hastened to White Horse Mountain bearing sustenance and privately told others: "Sovereign and subject must have continuity from beginning to end." The present sovereign, recognizing his loyalty and long desiring to test his ability, appointed him Attendant Cavalier when the new administration began, and shortly thereafter promoted him to Minister of Revenue. Two years later he was transferred to the Ministry of Justice. When land disputes accumulated and laws seemed ineffectual, numerous voices raised complaint. The Chamberlain examined each case with discernment and rendered judgment, and no one bore resentment. While serving in court, whenever officials brought documents for his seal, if he found them improper, he would explain his reservations before signing—no careless matter, this.

    His wife, of the Gyeong clan, was the daughter of the Right Drafter Si-man and granddaughter of Councilor Jeong Hae. As wife she was obedient; as mother she set an example. They had three sons: Su, who loved antiquity and excelled in letters, passed the examination and held office, now serving as Minister of Military Records; Li, who also passed the examination and gained renown, now Governor of Gaeseong; and Jae, an officer-designate pursuing his studies. Three daughters all predeceased him. His sons-in-law are Kim Sakgyeom, Recorder of the Royal Clan; Yi Changno, Right Censor; and Yeom Heungbang, Minister of Military Records. He had four grandsons: Ujbok, an officer; Seonbok; and two younger; and five granddaughters. His grandsons by marriage include Kim Yu and two granddaughters. He was to be buried on the eleventh month, on the day Gapsin, at the south slope of Seogok in Imjin County. When Su and Heungbang came seeking this inscription, I could not refuse, for the Chamberlain's sons and sons-in-law are my friends.

    The Chamberlain was compassionate and frugal, his every action guided by ritual propriety. Though the wisdom to order the realm lay dormant within him, never to be deployed in full governance of the state—such is heaven's design—his conduct bore no flaw, his children rose to prominence through his teaching, and at his passing he received an honorable posthumous name. This alone suffices to transmit his memory to posterity, and there is nothing to regret.

    The inscription reads:

    Grandson of Munhae,
    Son of Sasuk,
    Brothers of worth and grace,
    Successors to ancestral virtue.

    Serving King Chungjeong,
    His faithfulness knew no wavering.
    The sovereign asked not of his loyalty,
    But tested his ability.

    Twice he journeyed to the Yuan court,
    Returning each time to the sovereign's praise.
    The world said: His time has come.
    Yet the Chamberlain withdrew.

    Such heights were rarely seen,
    Yet his course was cut short.
    Who shall divine heaven's reason?
    I compose this poem
    To question the ages yet to come.
